The Republican Strategy of Resistance to Obama's Re-Election
The Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to fight falsifications in the elections.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, arguing that cases of election fraud in the United States are more rare than deaths from lightning strikes.
In addition, Republican lawyers counted only 300 cases of electoral falsification in the United States in ten years.
One thing can be said with confidence: these new trends will have a negative impact on the turnout of voters.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, the United States is responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
That is why most state governments since 2009 have passed laws that complicate the process of registration or voting.
This phenomenon gained new momentum after the November 2010 election, which brought Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills limiting voting rights in 41 states were passed in just one year in 2011.
The new election laws require the voter to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws shorten the period of early voting, abolish the right of registration of the voter on the day of the will and deprive citizens of the right to vote who are guilty.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of the Indiana law in 2008.
The republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have initiated bills that require voters to present ID cards with photographs in 34 states.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have such a universal identity card as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11 percent of U.S. citizens—that is, 21 million people who have reached the age required to vote—do not have an identity card with a photograph issued by their state’s government.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 did not have such a document.
At the same time, the cost of obtaining the required identity card often exceeds a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
In fact, 25 percent of African Americans, 15 percent of people earning less than $35,000, 18 percent of citizens over the age of 65, and 20 percent of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
But that's not all.
Voter students who are believed to vote for Democratic candidates are not allowed to use a photo ID issued by their school in several states.
But those same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs that vote mostly for Republicans to use the certificates issued by those clubs for voting.
Until 2004, no state required proof of U.S. citizenship to vote.
For the first time, such a requirement was introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than 10 states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are obviously aimed at limiting the voting of Latinos.
It is estimated that two-thirds of Latin American voters vote in favor of the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers initiated in 2011 laws abolishing voter registration on the day of the vote in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to provide assistance to those wishing to register.
This restriction did not pass without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, the voter registration campaign helped to list about 10 million citizens.
At the same time, measures taken since 2009 have led to a 17% drop in the level of registration of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in five other states passed laws aimed at reducing the period of early voting.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of early voters were African-American, although the latter accounted for only 13% of the state’s total electorate.
The same was true of those from Latin America.
Representing only 11% of voters, they made up 24% of citizens who voted early.
In contrast to whites, who formed 76 percent of voters, only 46 percent of those who voted early.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters are actively opposed to the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills were vetoed by Democratic governors.
The most ambiguous laws were suspended with the intervention of the United States Attorney General.
This allowed to partially limit the negative consequences.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring photo IDs.
However, the new rules that have come into force will certainly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Critics of the Democrats condemn the biased laws that have been passed, seeing them as an obvious focus on influencing the results of the 2012 election in key states.
The Brennan Center’s 2011 report shows that the states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral college to win the presidential election.
It is too early to argue with confidence that these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
Only one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the turnout of voters.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
