Higgs boson in detail
Last summer, a report that scientists may have been able to detect the Higgs boson caused a real stir - and not without reason.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all the particles in the universe, neither much nor little.
In addition, it is the last particle predicted to exist in the Standard Model — our best, or at least the “least imperfect” description of nature and the behavior of matter — but which has not previously been detected experimentally.
But physicists are not yet completely sure that it is the Higgs boson.
We know, without a shadow of a doubt, that we are dealing with a really new particle and that it strongly resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, the new data presented this week at a major physical congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, although some data is not yet sufficient for full confidence.
Let’s imagine, however, that we are talking about the Higgs boson, since the chances of making a mistake seem minimal, and let’s see what it means.
There is, in this world, one law absolutely inevitable, which says that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to circumvent this rule, do not even try too hard, otherwise harm yourself.
But although elementary particle physics is a rather strange world, it turns out that it also has one law of a similar nature: Pauli’s exclusion principle, which posits that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same “quantum state”—that is, some of their “states” are in common.
Based on this, physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find good-natured citizens, called fermions, who wisely obey the Pauli principle.
In another, the bosons, a sinister band of anarchists who have no respect for anything — at least for this principle, which means they can rest assured to be in the same place at the same time.
As reported by the site (by the way, completely unusual) Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratory, these bosons are divided, in turn, into two groups: mesons, which we will not talk about here, and "particle of force", by means of which the main forces of nature are distributed and to which in some way the boon belongs.
These same bosons, it should be emphasized, are not all such exotic creatures as you might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it’s thanks to one incredibly banal boson: a photon, or “particle of light,” which is the “courier” of electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a single particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it “disrupts” the electromagnetic field at that particular location, much like a stone thrown into a pond.
From this "violation" an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the bosons of the "transporters of force".
A more stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the only difference being that in order for this boson to appear, another field, the Higgs field, must be "broken".
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it is necessary to achieve very and very high energies, as if it were a frozen pond, the surface of which could only be shaken by a very large stone.
That’s why you need a huge particle accelerator like the one used in CERN – the Large Hadron Collider, which is a ring with a diameter of 27 km! – to achieve such huge energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is also useful for explaining the relationship between the Higgs boson and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact, others do not: a sheet of paper, for example, will never stick to the refrigerator itself.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have mass, while others (such as a photon, by the way) do not.
So, what can all these studies "bring" Mrs. Plamondon asks?
In science, they are used to verify the correctness of the Standard Model (SM), and this also allows physicists to sense the difference between the results of observations and the predictions of the SM.
In addition, some of them passionately yearn for such a discrepancy to be discovered, because the slightest discrepancy can open the door to "new physics" and close some of the Model's holes.
The latter, it must be said, still has significant drawbacks, offering no explanation for gravity (oh!) or for dark matter, which forms about 80% of the universe (oh!).
But so far, no such differences have been found in CERN.
Implications
The benefits of these studies for the daily life of the average person are harder to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that it is not.
In the early 1960s, pioneers of laser research at Bell’s labs couldn’t even guess what a revolution their work would bring.
They predicted their applications in science, but no more.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (previously impulsive) in 1962, said that the laser was originally viewed rather as a "laboratory gadget".
Imagine...
In addition, the application can be found for the toolkit accompanying the study.
For example, the same William Boyle during his optical research in 1969 developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, although it was not its original purpose at all, now serves as an “eye” for all digital cameras in the world and has earned the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Large Hadron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it only shows, in fact, that everything can be.
