The problem of access to palliative care
It is estimated that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care that is provided to alleviate the suffering of patients who have entered the final stage of their lives, whether at home, in a hospital or in a ward.
And some institutions, such as the Victor Gadbou Shelter and the Greater Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is this large gap in Quebec’s health care system that causes many palliative care practitioners to fear the adoption of a law legalizing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Beginning in October, a manifesto signed by palliative care lights, Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lyapuant, has been circulating, testifying to their disagreement with such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christian Martel, Quebec’s health care system is not effective enough to ensure the right to high-quality palliative care before the transition to euthanasia is allowed.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who spent 14 days in the emergency room in terrible pain, and no one took the necessary steps to relieve them.
I'm afraid patients only want to die because they don't get adequate care.
