When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she told me that she was sorry that I was stopping the fight.
She told me that my days were numbered.
There is no omnipotent care.
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank the medical staff for not fulfilling their request after the palliative care team eases their pain.
However, it should be noted that palliative care is not absolutely omnipotent in the fight against pain.
According to Elsie Monroe, director of palliative care at the Greater Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, patients are not susceptible to pain relief in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, in which the patient sleeps until the moment of his death, either from time to time or constantly.
We can no longer pretend that we do not know about these sufferings.
Increasingly, patients who fail to relieve pain will be able to have access to palliative sedation.
Those who suffer from pain always say the same thing: “I want to die.”
But it doesn’t necessarily mean “I want to be euthanized,” it means “I want to be made easier.”
