The bitcoin rate, peaking at $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, fell five months later to $2 before returning today to about $10 (the rates are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing special compared to the global exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) in its report on virtual currency, published in October, was interested in this system.
He describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies, such as “credits” used to promote a video game, which are earned during the game or which can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But exchange operations are always controlled and handled by a central body.
In Bitcoin, all the nodes of the network are simultaneously holders of the ledger, auditors, currency issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses, much like an e-mail.
Only for each new payment can the user choose a different address, thus providing anonymity.
The set of information relating to this transaction is signed electronically, using a dual-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is possible to check that the bitcoins used in the transaction actually exist in a public ledger sent across the network.
The key step is to register a new transaction in this book.
It passes through the solution of a mathematical problem sent to computers, which, like a temporary central bank, is given the privilege of adding this new line.
It is a phase of hashing a file, that is, converting a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers “take” a new transaction and add a number to it before they “hash” it all together.
The goal is to find a number that will give you a unique digital signature (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes easily check that it is correct.
The transaction thus becomes inextricably linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If, in order to deceive the user very quickly (less than ten minutes) would like to pay twice with the same money, only one of these two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would remain unconfirmed, since they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solves the problem gets 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the reward is regularly split in half, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of Bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divided up to one hundred million, which leaves another reserve...
The complexity of the task also increases with the increase in computing power.
The life of the network has already experienced ups and downs.
Sites providing Bitcoin services were attacked, and Bitcoins were stolen from the reserves.
“The defect used does not apply to the protocol itself,” said Pierre Nouza, who recently launched Paymium, a company that makes payments in real money using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reported on the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this drawback.
Major players, such as Wikipedia, refuse to accept donations of this kind.
Others, such as the WordPress blog platform, allow them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the ledger and found that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
"Giant Sales" was announced in November.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” rejoices Jon Holmqvist, who works at Coinabul, which is engaged in the conversion of bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Nouza, another author of this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as an operational network.
Its system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (in real money) or contactless payment via a mobile phone, but it uses Bitcoin to check transactions, which is thus cheaper.
The owner better controls his personal data and can thus be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for entrepreneurs who do not need to install new devices or software.
It is enough to communicate the address, which can be "photographed and recognized" by phone, Pierre Nouza specifies, assuring that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general tendency to revise hierarchical systems in favor of more horizontal ones.
“Before Bitcoin is approved, it will take some time, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
By the way, the ECB’s report envisages reviewing the various risks that are considered to be elevated today if this system is successful.
