Births of the Constitution of Egypt
This is a new risky step by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever, on the issue of a constitutional declaration that temporarily gives it extraordinary powers, it has decided to play va-bank.
To everyone’s surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on the final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state gave the Assembly two additional months to complete the work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has relied on a preliminary text, which has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal contradictions.
This new initiative only strengthened the country’s division.
According to his opponents, the President persists in his "autocratic delusion", continuing to "violate this word" and "violate the law".
In the camp of his followers, they are convinced that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis by accelerating the transition process.
The referendum must be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time, which forces the Brethren to abandon the intention to explain to the Egyptians the text, the article after the article.
For the president, it is also a way to restore public and democratic legitimacy, while discontent rages across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favor, as he told the American weekly Time in an interview.
Moreover, the call for an accelerated vote resembles an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: “Either you vote for my text, or I leave to myself extraordinary powers”, which are supposed to be completed after the adoption of the Constitution.
In this strange atmosphere, 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamists, voted yesterday for the text.
Most liberals have not responded to the challenge.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they knocked on the door, feeling unable to give their opinion.
Representatives of human rights defenders, religious minorities or civil society did the same.
To achieve the required quorum, 11 alternate participants were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, in most cases, the articles were voted unanimously.
The commentators, by the way, were distracted by the fact that one of the few disagreements of the day arose around...time for prayer, as some members of the committee felt that the Hours of the Constituent Assembly were wrongly tuned.
The text, which was voted on yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
The subject of universal attention, article 2 ultimately remained the same article from the 1971 Constitution, which stated that "the principles of sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for which the implementation of Islamic law is one of the main requirements, hoped to replace the "principles" with "rules" that would allow them to be applied more strictly.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is a testament to their goodwill and respect for other members of Egyptian society.
“Hypocrisy,” say the liberals, who only see it as a PR.
Because, in their opinion, the Islamization of the Constitution occurs through other articles.
They point in particular to article 220, which gives the University of Al-Azhar an advisory role, in particular with regard to verifying compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pomier, this is alarming, because “people who are called to make decisions are not elected and do not have any democratic legitimacy.”
We can see the birth of theocracy.”
Many liberals, moreover, are agitated by the fact that the next rector of this university seems to be far less moderate than the current one.
“At the moment, there is no specific religious intervention.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of civil law.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulema, but people with a university education, some have studied in the French system,” says Alexis Bloe, who is preparing a dissertation on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he admits that “there may be ambiguities around Article 220, as the terms used in it are borrowed from religious lexicon.
This applies in particular to the “fiqh” [Islamic jurisprudence].
And in the future, there may be a question of how competent civil judges are to make decisions about this.”
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is subject to criticism as it gives broad powers to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim brothers claim that they have significantly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another controversial point: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the consideration of the defense budget will be held not in the Parliament, but in the National Defense Council.
Nor will the trial of civilians in military courts be prohibited, despite requests from human rights associations.
The latter also expressed concern about the text, which they considered to be detrimental to freedom.
Responsibility for blasphemy remains, and insults are now prohibited, which can have serious consequences for freedom of speech, and especially for freedom of the press.
In addition, none of the articles speaks anymore about the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Moraef, of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture in article 36.
A word that did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was due to speak on television last night, the demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state, in turn, will take to the streets on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for holy places, the Pup of the Earth and the sea from the brine
The Promised Land combines the grandeur of biblical truths, modern comfort and the primacy of nature.
The AIF has identified five of the most important reasons to visit Israel.
