To him from the foot of the mountain delivers a shuttle bus.
The total length of the ski runs is 45 km.
According to ancient tradition, there were supposedly pagan gods living on the top of the mountain.
Visiting unique museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You can't go on one trip at all.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are worth visiting.
Among them is the Museum of Israel, located near the Knesset (parliament).
It houses the oldest Cumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea Scrolls, found in the caves of the Jewish desert, and about 500,000 archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
It is also worth visiting the Museum of Art in Tel Aviv.
In his exposition are widely presented paintings of impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cezanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso.
In Akko you can visit the Al Basha Bath Museum, which represents several halls of ancient Turkish baths with paintings of visitors and bathers of the time.
In Caesarea it is worth entering the unique partial Rally Museum, where you can admire the sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are no tour guides and souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are categorically not accepted.
The fifth – the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv – tells of one of the most dramatic pages in history.
The most tragic section - a children's memorial - is built in memory of 1.5 million children destroyed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and you find yourself in absolute darkness.
They beat the stars.
And the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is mentioned there as well.
Rejoice
Israel’s three main resort areas are located on the shores of the Mediterranean, Red and Dead Seas.
Each of them has pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Interestingly, the Red Sea is bathed even in the winter months, as the water temperature there does not drop below 21 degrees of heat, and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The dead sea is even warmer, and they swim there all year round.
By the way, this is the most unusual sea in the world is at the lowest point on the planet - 417 m below sea level.
The azure water in it is a brine that easily holds on to the float even those who do not know how to swim at all.
The scenery around it is unreal.
They come here to undergo a course of treatment with the use of salt water - rapeseed, and curative dirt, and to cure health in dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes mellitus, to put in order the weakened nerves.
Touching the secrets of antiquity
They are kept by the ancient part of Tel Aviv - the town of Jaffo on the shore of the Mediterranean Sea.
Through it passed the famous Sea Route, connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom they lived a long and happy life.
Tourists love to wander through the narrow streets named after the signs of the Zodiac.
They say that if you lean against the walls on the street "your" sign, Fortune will become favorable.
In Jaffa you can meet newlyweds coming from all over Israel and even other countries for photo shoots.
And in Caesarea - the city of King Herod - you can wander through the Roman theater, "take" the fortress of the Crusaders.
During the Roman period, Caesarea was the capital of Judea and the residence of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
