In recent days, there has been a wave of protests against low wages in Walmart department stores and restaurants of popular fast-food chains such as McDonald's, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy's and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
Until then, no one is going to predict whether this wave will turn into the ninth wave or it is destined to die out in the early stages.
The actions are supported by trade unions and a number of left-wing public organizations.
In addition to raising the modest salaries that ordinary Walmart workers and the fast food system receive, the goal of protest organizers is to create trade union organizations in them.
So far, this sector of the economy is almost not covered by the trade union movement.
46 cents a year?
The action began last week, after Thanksgiving, on the so-called “Black Friday,” when an orgy of cheap sales collapsed on America, capturing millions of residents and sometimes accompanied by riots.
On this day, some employees of Walmart, which employs 2.2 million people worldwide, left their jobs and picketed with trade unions and left-wing activists the stores of the corporation, whose goods are intended for people of modest and medium wealth.
Walmart sells everything in the world, from diapers, hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The products in its stores are on average from 8% to 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That’s why many of Walmart’s low-wage workers only get paid at work.
The availability and range of products made Walmart one of the largest corporations in America.
According to critics, Walmart can afford to sell goods at a discount in part because it pays its employees little.
The latter also complain about difficult working conditions, for example, the lack of forklifts or manual scanners.
Shareholders in Black Friday demanded an increase in wages and said the cost of health insurance provided by the corporation had jumped from $30 to $100 a month.
The typical Walmart worker, who gets $9.5 an hour, this expense is not in his pocket, they said.
Scientists from the University of California at Berkeley prove that if Walmart raises the average salary to $12 an hour, it will cost the corporation $3.2 billion.
That’s about 1.1% more than she spends on her salary right now.
If Walmart completely shifts the growth of wages on the shoulders of buyers, then every visit to the store will cost them only 46 cents more.
In a year, they will spend about $12.39 more than they do now.
Walmart’s supporters say the protests have occurred in only nine states and have not caused any damage to the corporation.
Black Friday continued in its stores from 8 p.m. on Thursday to midnight the next day, during which time Walmart sold about 5,000 items per second.
In total, its cash registers produced almost 100 million transactions on Black Friday.
Dan Fogelman, a spokesman for the corporation, told the Huffington Post that fewer than five Walmart employees had left their jobs in total, and that the protest was just another “piarous trick” by the union that organized it.
"Free cash!"
The protests continued this week in New York City, where their object was not Walmart department stores (they are not complaining in this progressive city, and therefore they are not here yet), and McDonald's and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald’s says it sells billions of servings, and after that it doesn’t even give you hospitals or pay you for honest work!
Julien Williams, Member of the New York City Council
At the moment, the minimum wage, according to federal and New York law, is $7.25 per hour.
Fast-food restaurants raise it over time, but not much, and on average their regular workers get $8.90 an hour in New York City.
No one earns less in this expensive city.
How it is possible to exist in New York for such money, for me it is incomprehensible.
Once, a quarter of American teenagers who worked behind their backs after school, while living with their parents, passed through the McDonald’s.
Few saw this as the main source of food or planned to stay there for a long time.
Right now I’m constantly coming across interviews with McDonald’s employees who complain that they have to live on that salary and sometimes even feed their children on it.
On the other hand, on the forum of the Wall Street Journal there is a comment, the author of which notes that it is irresponsible to raise children if you do not know what you will feed them.
Protesters, who began at 6:30 a.m. on Thursday at McDonald’s on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that cashiers and fast food cooks start paying at least $15 an hour, more than doubling their current minimum wage.
They also demanded that trade union organizations be set up in the field of fast food.
U.S. law prohibits the administration from obstructing and punishing trade union activists with harassment and dismissal.
