- What else is ahead?
Despite the fact that Kinect has moved the interaction to the physical level, a lot still happens on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information has improved (the system receives more data), and the output is not very much yet.
We are trying to change this, we are working on truly three-dimensional imaging systems based on different technologies, including projective ones.
We need to let the computer world into our physical world, make it more tangible.
To do this, however, you need to recognize not only the user, but also the space around him.
Then we can complement the real world with virtual objects in a much more convenient form.
And first of all - to hell with these stupid virtual reality helmets!
What do you think about voice control?
It's a popular thing, but isn't it overrated?
- It definitely can not be called a panacea - the question of privacy arises, because it does not always want to inform others about their actions and intentions.
In fact, all kinds of interactions with computers are good, but each in its own niche.
For example, for the management of devices in public places, we had a project in which we thought about gestures, but not about swaggering, but about such clumsy, short ones.
At the same time, the gestures were taken not by the camera of the device, but by a wristband, which fixed the movements of the bones and muscles.
While it is large, but theoretically it can be reduced to the size of the wristwatch.
But in general, the future behind a mixed type of control, for example, gesture + voice.
- How's that?
- For example, how would you ask me to give you this soda can?
You will say and show at the same time.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, it's gonna be very hard to tell.
- So you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or can not at the moment?
- Not necessarily, but it's a mutual rapprochement.
I think that in the near future we will mainly have to work on the development of new types of sensors that will allow us to more accurately determine human reactions.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, they give a good resolution in depth, this is very important.
- If we talk about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what are your claims to modern cameras?
Lack of depth, depth, or anything else?
- In principle, the current generation is something that can be pushed back in our work on three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be good to get megapixels 8 at a speed of 1000 c / s.
But it’s not about the megapixels themselves, but as a matrix and depth.
From the last point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us - it adds work to the designers of algorithms.
That is, it is necessary to remember not only about the resolution of the X and Y axes, but also Z.
Also very important is the speed, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic, and the current 30 cc is frankly small, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes from our Redmond laboratory made a touch sensor with adjustable processing delay - from 1 to 100 ms, with modern serial sensors closer to the second (60-100) indicator.
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction between humans and machines.
I would have been very useful in my work the equivalent of such a device, only not requiring touch, so that the frame per second was more.
