- Of course, all the time walking around, holding a smartphone in your hands is not very convenient, but here's what I think: the coolest option would be a "transitional" augmented reality, when based on the cloud platform you could switch from glasses to a smartphone, a projection screen and so on.
Glasses are a very personal device, this is their power (private things see only you), and at the same time weakness - augmented reality based on glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects together with other people.
Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to a mere mortal.
There is one problem that is often pointed out by critics of such an idea: there is no tactile feedback!
My hands don't feel anything!
What are your team’s responses to this challenge?
In my lectures, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in human-machine interaction.
I think the eighth may well be the addition of tactile sensations.
So far, one of the interesting tricks is the use of the second hand as a kind of substrate for the image.
It registers the clicks very well!
But there are also technologies that are really aimed at giving these “pictures in the air” touchability – for example, the interference of several directional ultrasounds at a certain point where the finger is located gives a feeling, but for now it is very weak – as if you were put on a pillow.
There are wristbands that affect the nerve endings in the fingers - also a promising direction.
Have you tried to fool your brain?
To make him think that he feels what he’s supposed to feel the moment he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried it yet.
Here is another task that has to fight for a long time - how to make a person physically in a very limited space, to believe that he is going on an open, almost infinite - we are also working on concepts of running paths (not at all like in clubs), moving platforms, as well as huge piles.
While deceiving the brain turns out to be average, the work is still very many years.
That’s what makes working on virtual reality so appealing to the researcher – many things in an absolutely incipient state.
