Poland and Space.
Last week, at a meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the former Eastern Bloc countries (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland began working closely with ESA in 1994 and over the next few years took an active part in a number of Agency projects.
But the journey to space in Poland began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in space flights, but this was not always met with understanding.
I would like to recall, for example, the lecture by A. Sternfeld, who presented ideas from his groundbreaking work “Introduction to Cosmonautics” at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on December 6, 1933.
The ideas of the young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after a few years Sternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934 in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltri and André Luis Hirsch Prize for "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899-1966), mentioned above, later became a great propagandist of astronomy and cosmonauts.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and has written a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a well-known world propagandist of spaceflight, and his contribution was appreciated, among other things, that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named in his honor.
Already in 1925 in Poland was built a railway girder equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should have been used to accelerate or brake the cart.
Information about this costume is known only from the press of that era.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery began to think about missile arrows.
The study was carried out by the Section of Weapons Technology in cooperation with Professors Mechislav Wolfka and Gustav Mokzhitsky.
From the preserved materials, it can be seen that the studies have reached the stage of practical tests.
But with the arrival of German troops, work was interrupted.
In 1937 in the specialized press appeared the idea of a photoelectric fighter rocket, which was proposed by the engineer Rogozinsky, and the following year came out the work "Air missile-torpedo and aviation missile-bomb" by the author Lelivy-Kzhivoblotsky.
Both projects were designed for military use of rocket engines.
Before the war itself, all projects for the military use of missile technology were carried out by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of work, the work was finished because of the beginning of the war.
The next scientific work on cosmonauts appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronauts (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time about the society is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the magazine "Problems", in which four voluminous articles on astronautics are published.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich proposed to organize a society that would be engaged in astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already gaining momentum, and it was clear that space exploration was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (POA) has been trying to join the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951), and in the autumn of the POA became its full member.
The following year, Kazimierz Zarankevich, the first chairman of the International Federation of Astronautics (1902-1959), became vice-chairman of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He remained in this position until his death, which occurred in 1959.
Since 1956, the POA has made a significant contribution to the development of a very successful meteorological missile RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish missile to carry out scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The missile, able to overcome a distance of 1800 m, was about 80 cm long, and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, two-stage tests of the RM-2 rocket were carried out on the Bled desert.
This rocket was about 1.4 m long, and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the rocket was already able to do real scientific work - the rocket RM-34 could overcome 14.5 km, and its task was to monitor the high-altitude wind.
In 1962, however, further development was halted.
The successor to the first RM rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm, and the initial weight - 32.5 kg.
Three types (designated Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed in the size of the camera for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a volume of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B - 0.34 liters, and Meteor-1C - 0.62 liters.
The maximum flight range for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Institute of Aviation was developing a Meteor-2 rocket, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a launch weight of 380 kg was able to lift a payload weighing 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Then were built versions of Meteor-2N and Meteor-3.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
In addition, as part of the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslav Hermashevsky became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
