The movie "Operation Argo": When there is nowhere worse, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of Islamist student demonstrators seized the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the overthrown Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi, who fled after the revolution in the United States, who had been the patron of his regime for decades.
The U.S. administration did not expect a positive outcome - it could not afford to throw the chess overboard, because it could fundamentally undermine the trust of allies in other countries.
However, to achieve the liberation of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later reinforced by a failed attempt to free the hostages by force.
The detained diplomats were finally released after 444 days, after talks brokered by the Algerian government.
Their fate caused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment at home.
The defeat in Iran greatly contributed to Jimmy Carter's defeat in the 1980 presidential election, which ended with the election of Ronald Reagan.
The film, directed by actor Ben Affleck, "Operation Argo" describes one of the episodes of the story that brought America small victories.
Shortly before the occupation of the embassy, six workers managed to escape.
After some difficult journeys, they ended up at the Canadian Embassy.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, aided by the extravagant legend of cover-up, according to which they went out on Canadian passports as members of the filming group, looking for a place in the country for filming a science fiction epic.
Combination of genres
The plan, invented by “evacuation” expert Tony Mendes, required Hollywood’s cooperation.
In order for the legend to be true, specialized magazines wrote about the project of the film, press conferences were held, the fictional production company had a real office.
Details of the operation have long been kept secret, a film based on the memoirs of Tony Mendes.
The film Affleck is a special combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a real political thriller, the so-called "movie-movie-opus", the story of a successful affair, an affair - an example may be a number of films about friends of Ocean.
The moods in the film are constantly changing - on the one hand, documentary scenes from Tehran (the titles show iconic historical photographs of events and how the same situations were demonstrated in the film - there are no big differences in this).
On the other hand, the lighter Hollywood passages intersect with irony and a moderate exaggeration.
And then scenes from the headquarters of the CIA and other institutions - men in suits discuss the situation at the negotiating tables, on the stairs of institutions, by phone ...
Ben Affleck did a great job of restarting his career.
From the ridiculed actor became a respected director, and his game ceased to be an object of ridicule.
"Operation Argo" is his third full-length film, after the dark detective "Goodbye, Baby, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "City" (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck’s first film, which is not filmed in the director’s hometown of Boston.
The feeling of the atmosphere of the place at the same time refers to the qualities that elevated the director's earlier films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck demonstrates this in Argo, where Tehran is “playing” Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place on the streets, while reconstructing real events - the opening scenes of the fall of the embassy impress with their clarity, which also conveys the emotions of confusion and unpredictability that arise when somewhere suddenly history changes.
A similar effect is achieved by Affleck and his colleagues in the scenes of the fictional (fake headquarters on the Tehran bazaar).
Too many processes in too many places.
The director had to deal with the fact that the story does not involve many exciting scenes of cinematic significance.
He works quite successfully with this few, sometimes he thinks something up - there it all comes out not so elegantly (the scene in which a phone call in America prevents the impending crisis at Tehran airport, and the chase on the runway looks rather over-the-top).
The disadvantage of "Argo" is the distraction associated with the need to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman in the role of Hollywood colleagues are really very charming, but their characters would deserve more space, and they are not the only ones in the film.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of drama, it is a film that can be watched with moderate interest, appreciating the staging and retro style that recreates the thrillers of the seventies.
But it's hard to capture.
However, this is enough to remind one, still in a certain sense of living history, as well as to testify to how exaggerated are the notions of omnipotent and omniscient intelligence services.
