MVRDV architects prove that true adventures are not only in the imagination - on the example of Speakenisse and his newly built Book Mountain - 2 photos
“This building seems fun to me, it looks futuristic, finally we can see something interesting again,” says Lizette Verhaig, walking on the edge of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT specialist at a nearby large enterprise, thinks like this: “No, this building is really beautiful.”
But I ask myself: why do we have another library today?
Everyone has the Internet, iPad, and e-books.
Now no one voluntarily goes to such old-fashioned libraries, right?
Spekkenisse, an unremarkable sleepy town near Rotterdam, holds an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 people has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
To combat this annoying circumstance, it was decided a few years ago to contribute to general education and to build seven imaginary bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes, in the form of painted miniatures made of reinforced concrete.
The success of this educational initiative was modest.
And then the city fathers realized that they had the only chance to beat the statistics: to build a library here!
Vinnie Maas of the Rotterdam architectural bureau MVRDV, a master of bold bar charts and the author of witty, sometimes even cynical constructions, took on the task with his usual impatience and appeared at a competition audition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a nod to his face.
And while the members of the jury looked puzzled and shrugged, the daring Maas composed from his original gift a pyramid in size and concluded the speech in defense of his project with the following words: "Dear citizens!"
Here it is, my proposal: "Book Mountain" in Spekeniss, the so-called Buchenberg!
Nine years later, this mountain, worth 30 million euros, has grown.
It is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground garage, supermarket, post office and several adjacent residential houses and townhouses totaling 50 apartments.
In early November, the Book Mountain was awarded the second prize of the competition "Best Library of the Netherlands 2012".
The project also participates in the national Dutch wooden building competition of 2012.
Thus, the impersonal suburb, which previously could not offer anything except a postmodernist pedestrian zone and the surprisingly ugly town hall, whose white facades suggest a dairy, became richer for one modern work of architecture.
But most importantly, the first public building of cultural purpose in the history of this town appeared in Speakenisse.
The Long Road to the Book
First impression: the book Eldorado under the cap for cheese.
There is only one elevator passing in the center of the mountain range, because real fans of architecture and reading will prefer to explore this area on foot.
Glassed on all sides, the room is bright and easily seen, floors made of burnt brick and elegant street lights create a sense of public urban space.
The urban environment is perfectly recreated.
Look involuntarily looking for benches, dogs and playing football boys and girls.
And everywhere - books, books, books.
“Usually the bookshelves stand along the facades, and in the middle there is a large dark hall, usually uncomfortable and faceless,” says Vinny Maas.
We put the classic configuration of the space from the foot to the head and pulled out the reading area from the inside out.
The inner space of the mountain is skillfully used: in the center there are offices, Internet library, chess club, environmental center and technical premises.
Especially pleased are the black bookshelves, which serve as wall decoration, parapets, and stair railings.
Their appearance, texture and smell are unusual.
Even experienced architects and engineers-builders get lost in guessing what this unknown material is.
“We wanted to work with secondary materials,” explains Yop Trauborst, project manager representing the Speakenisse community, according to the standard’s requirements.
And once at an agricultural enterprise in Frisia, we found a suitable by-product of agriculture.
For many years in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands, artificial fibrous material of millimeter thickness has been used as a substrate for roots.
It is cheap and saves time.
Thin textiles serve one or two seasons, after which it can be thrown away.
For the library, this canvas - for the first time in such volumes - was pressed into a four-centimeter-thick panel.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbauplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, uniform, durable material, a little like a new car and a little sneakers.
There are 105 steps to the top.
Anyone who overcomes the path of almost 500 meters in length will be rewarded in a literary cafe not only with fantastic views of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and wooden ficus in pots.
They care about the atmosphere, and first of all about the correct humidity of the air on the literary mountain.
The Cost of a New Soul
“It’s hard to believe, but this building, despite its many glass surfaces, is an exemplary project in terms of ecology,” says Trouborst.
The heat of the earth is used for its heating and cooling.
Although the Book Mountain is under a glass cap, even on clear days the sun gets inside only for a short time.
Large farms made of glued wood, located perpendicularly to the glass facade, give shade and take on most of the sun's rays.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
The rest of the protection is provided by fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the IT skeptic mentioned above, has already visited the new library.
Lizette Verhayg was already here.
Also, traditional Chinese medicine teacher Cynthia Bogard, who called Buchenberg "the soul of Speakenisse, which has long been lacking."
The reason: a few weeks before the opening, each resident received an invitation to donate one book from his own collection.
These books were to take up empty seats on the shelves of a library not yet fully stocked - at that time there were 70,000 books in it.
The idea worked.
The shelves are up.
“There’s nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Vinnie Maas.
“I think that thanks to our invitation now every resident is somehow connected to this new home.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's just for decoration.
Thus, MVRDV managed to solve the royal task, which in professional jargon is called identity creation.
Spokenesse wrote his own literary history.
Let them be very young and uneducated.
This is just the starting point for identity building.
Sabo: "The Germans must play a more important role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stefan Sabo, an expert on U.S.-European relations, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic path.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first made it clear that it would vote against the Palestinian request for observer status at the United Nations.
Berlin abstained from the vote.
Why? Why?
Stefan Sabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany now needs to be cautious about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that she does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence, without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting on the introduction of a no-fly zone.
In the end, NATO implemented this proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely, from the policy, which, so to speak, was run by the United States, to the German foreign policy itself.
The situation is further complicated by the fact that Europeans do not have a coherent unified policy.
Thus, the Germans again find themselves between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that so far they are only sensing their role, but are on the way to a “more normal” foreign policy.
Such a foreign policy as is carried out by France or the United Kingdom.
What exactly does “normal” foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is a willingness to take a position in their national interest that does not depend on the position of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, on exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are very different from those of other major states, and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf states.
Therefore, it needs to be careful not to offend the public and the elites in Arab countries.
In any case, it plays a role.
But I wouldn’t attach too much importance to that, it’s not a completely one-sided connection.
But in any case, it plays an important role in the calculations of the Germans.
Has Germany harmed its relations with the United States by refraining from making important decisions, such as voting on Palestine?
I am sure that understanding of the German position prevails in Europe and even in the United States.
So I don’t think it was as dramatic a snag as the Libyan issue.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect in this way.
After all, this signals that she should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that her interests should be taken into account.
There are differing views in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The U.S., on the contrary, has clearly expressed its support for the veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the United States and many European countries?
Because of American domestic politics, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama administration has a deep understanding of the European position.
But due to the local political situation, the government, of course, cannot openly take such a position.
I believe that the significant differences in opinion are not as significant as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about Netanyahu’s policies.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the US on the one hand and the position of the most important partner in the EU on the other?
I think that is what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a single, uncontested European policy, but now it is not.
Therefore, they cannot take a broader approach and are forced to act instead, relying only on their own vision of the situation.
This is what they do with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take a leading role in developing a common European position.
It is clear that this is not easy for Germany, at least because of its ties with Israel.
This topic has always been tricky.
But I think it is clear to the Germans that they should play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, will it not really take the lead?
Or is the leading role still hard to give to Germany?
Germany is not yet used to this, it is still always unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is always difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis - every time Germany takes on an important role, there are various anti-German feelings.
The Germans don't just deal with it.
Actually, it’s an old problem: you don’t want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It should take into account the most different neighbors and opinions, and this is not easy.
So, the influence of the US in European politics is constantly weakening, but at the moment the EU does not fill this vacuum, who then remains?
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
