What are the most important diseases that are transmitted sexually?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and tripper (gonorrhea).
Common viral STIs are HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes, and hepatitis.
Frontal pediculosis and scabies refer to parasitic STIs.
What are the main affected groups?
Syphilis and gonorrhea occur mainly in men who have sex with men.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, at least four out of every five cases of syphilis in Germany are transmitted through sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, the most common sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydia infections, trichomoniasis, candidiasis (fungus), gonorrhea and human papillomavirus.
The prevalence of HIV among heterosexual adults is relatively low, but about 20 per cent of new HIV infections are in this group.
Among young people, chlamydia infections are significantly more common than among other groups of the population.
