Many judges also said they did not want to watch the referendum, which would render it invalid.
"The Qur'an is our Constitution"
The well-organized Muslim Brotherhood, in turn, called for the opposite demonstration, but, with caution, not in Tahrir Square, but after a mass prayer on the other bank of the Nile in front of the Cairo University.
It was attended by a large number of women under the veils and Salafi adherents who shouted: “The people demand the application of God’s law.”
They demanded of Morsi: "Cleanse the land!" and assured him: "The Qur'an is our constitution."
The struggle for power over the symbolic square, on which it all began, provoked a state of almost civil war.
Morsi's followers obviously didn't want to take that risk.
The Muslim Brotherhood said that both opponents and supporters of the draft constitution spoke out loud and clearly.
Now is the time to let the people decide at the ballot box in which direction the country should go.
For most Islamists, this is considered a decided thing.
“The concept of ‘human rights’ is never mentioned.”
Hafiz Abu Saeed is furious at this forced constitutional process, which, in fact, was supposed to last until February with the participation of all public forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and the chairman of the Egyptian Human Rights Organization (EHR) defended the Muslim Brotherhood when they were in prison or in court under Mubarak.
Not because he shared their worldview, but because human rights are indivisible to him.
For this he was beaten, sentenced, arrested.
And now the words "human rights" are never found in the new constitution, he regrets in conversation with "Welt am Sonntag".
The extension of Morsi’s influence to all three branches of government in the state disappoints the lawyer.
These measures represent clear blows to the democratic rules of the game and will lead the Egyptians to a new dictatorship.
“Instead of strengthening the civilian state, the president de facto annulled it,” Saeed said.
Without civil society organizations, democracy cannot function.
Saeda feels that everyone has left him, even the international community, which looks at the ideological struggle of the directions on the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
There may be a reward for this.
A protester in Tahrir Square warns, “You’re creating a monster that you can’t control.”
Norwegian rakfisk: the most smelly fish in the world?
Norway’s population of five million is one of the highest living standards not only in Europe, but also worldwide.
Perhaps the secret of this country’s success is somehow linked to a local addiction to one extremely sinister fish dish?
Take a few overripe pieces of cheese.
Put them in a bunch of dirty and sweaty sports clothes.
Leave them there for a week.
You will get a pungent smell of rakfisk - one of the most famous Norwegian delicacies.
I'm in a small town called Fagernes, three hours' drive from Oslo.
Around the snow-covered picturesque views. It is very beautiful, but in the air there is an inexhaustible characteristic smell.
Rakfisk is a trout, sprinkled with salt and floating in the water for up to a year, depending on what kind of soul you need to achieve.
As dusk thickens and cools, crowds of Norwegians gather for a festival in Fagernes, dedicated to this very, let’s say, exciting dish.
“They eat it raw and drink it with a hint of aquavit, the local vodka,” explains Howard Halvarsen, a local firefighter by profession and co-founder of the “Raccoon General” who runs the festival.
All around us people eat fish cut in small cubes and drink it in large portions of alcohol.
“Somebody likes aquavit more than rakfisk,” says Howard.
This drink is able to stop the smell.
I'll try a couple of pieces.
If you manage to carry a piece under your nose, then everything is not so bad - little is different from the portion of land that you have carried with you for a long time on the bus.
Rakfisk is a Norwegian product from very different times, times of poverty, when, even before the appearance of refrigerators, fish were soaked in hermetically sealed barrels with salt water in the autumn.
Then, in the deep winter, when the fish had already thoroughly and thoroughly fertilized, it was extracted and, after smothering the perception of alcohol, consumed in food.
In memory of the last generation, the fact that thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work and emigrate, mainly to the United States.
Now the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, who are attracted by jobs, high salaries and a developed social security system.
Residents of Sweden (a long-time rival, and not so long ago and a much more sheltered neighbor) come here en masse to work.
Rakfisk is perceived as an important symbol, an indispensable, though somewhat sinister, element of Norway’s past.
It is one of the most expensive local dishes.
On the other hand, everything is expensive here - a small glass of beer or a sandwich will cost you <0xC2><0xA3>9 ($14).
Norway rarely appears in the world’s news, and most of the country’s residents seem to like it.
People here are still reluctant to mention the name of Anders Breivik, a racist and right-wing extremist who shot and killed 77 men, women and children last year.
Without mentioning his name, the attack is called “the July 22 incident.”
It is very difficult for Norwegians to believe that in their peaceful country one of their fellow citizens was capable of such atrocities and murders.
Norway’s current prosperity is based on the growth (since the early 1970s) of one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world.
“Oil, however, is not the only reason for our prosperity,” says Anna, our waitress, carrying trays with a durable rakfisko, a woman with long light hair and strikingly blue eyes, the embodiment of Nordic well-being.
We are a people of understanding, as you call it.
Like most Norwegians, she speaks excellent English.
We don't like to show off, we don't brag.
Norway is very careful with its oil - most of the revenues of the oil and gas industry is invested in a special fund created for the benefit of future generations.
In the years leading up to the global financial crisis, when everyone was squandering money they didn’t have, Norway was carefully calculating all costs.
“As long as you can ski in the winter and hike in the summer, that’s enough for happiness,” says Anna.
"And there's rakfisk," she adds with a carefree laugh.
I stand in the snow in the queue for some food - rakfiska is enough for me.
Here is a hamburger with salmon meat - it's definitely exotic, delicious juicy meat.
But in the evening we are waiting for even more of the same fish with an unforgettable smell.
In my hotel there is a special dinner dedicated to rakfisk, during which visitors by voting determine the best or perhaps the most fragrant fish.
There's a live TV show showing the leader in a tie-button, surrounded by plates with rakfisko.
This is similar to the Eurovision Song Contest.
"So, Thor Jurgen, what's your assessment of the best fish out there in the mountains?"
"Yes, Howard, here's our assessment."
Everyone laughs and applauds.
Someone falls from a chair, perhaps by taking over the aquavit.
Or maybe just the smell of that fish.
Mexican President Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto will have a difficult start to his career.
As Mexican President-elect Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant invites us to look at the difficulties he will face and the mixed expectations of his country’s population.
The traffic in Mexico City is in a particularly dire state.
This city is overcrowded with transport and at the best of times, and since Monday, steel dams have been erected that cut several key highways to the capital and caused chaos on the roads.
However, this was done not to prevent people from getting to work from the suburbs, but to prevent protesters from getting to the parliament building.
On Sunday, Mexico’s new president, Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto, will wear a presidential tie and take the country’s reins.
He has a difficult task ahead of him.
Mexico has achieved good economic performance under the administration of Felipe Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n, who is now in power, but the country is immersed in the war on drugs, which in six years has already claimed about 60,000 lives.
“My government is declaring to the people of Mexico its readiness to fight violence,” Mr. Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office of the White House earlier this week.
I am going to propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this goal.
Prior to such statements, Mr. Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto's political career developed alongside the President of the United States as governor of his native Mexico State.
In his homeland, in the densely populated and vast state surrounding the country's capital, opinions about the new leader were divided.
A straight-line man
In the idyllic town of Valle de Bravo, for example, it is remembered with warmth.
Residents credit him with the revival of tourism, the development of the resort area and the creation of infrastructure.
The city can be reached by one of the new highways built by Mr. Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto, which are very different from the roads with quarries and pits that were previously at this place.
The plaques with his name hang on the modern building of the sports center and on the impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
“We are linking him with the hopes of real and serious change,” says his friend and political ally, Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a state congressman from the Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto-led Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI).
We look forward to the real and decisive changes that are so urgently needed in our country, especially in the area of security and economic development.
After 81 years of continuous rule, PRI was ousted in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olivera admits that after his 12-year absence from the presidential palace of Los Pinos, the party has high hopes for Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto.
In addition, he denies the accusations of inconsistency put forward by the opposition to the new president.
He is very straightforward and very committed to the realization of his vision of the future of the country.
He is an excellent statesman and, above all, a man who is able to listen.
But in another part of the state, many people have a different idea about the former governor.
The municipality of Nesaualkoyotl, also known as Ciudad Nesa, is the most striking contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle de Bravo.
Hidden under the highways, it is in many ways a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the municipality also have a severe character of this metropolis.
Earlier this year, troops had been drawn in to appease the drug-trafficking gangs in these areas, and violence against women was particularly acute.
In the last two years alone, several dozen bodies of murdered women have been found in the desert near a large dump.
More than a thousand women were killed in Mexico City during the governorate of Mr. Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto, far exceeding that figure in the notoriously violent city of Ciudad Ju<0xC3><0xA1>rez, whose name has come to be called when it comes to the murder of innocent women.
According to Mr. Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto ' s opponents, he could at best be said to have been unable to cope with the problem of killing women during his tenure as governor.
At worst, his administration is accused of completely ignoring the problem.
A resident of a concrete house, similar to most houses in this weary area, Irineya Buendia is struggling to contain her tears by showing me photos of her late daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes she was killed by her co-habitant.
“When I got to her house, it looked like her body had been washed before,” Buendia recalls.
There were signs that she was beaten, and the body was already cut.
Mariana’s mother retells this story, and the portrait of her daughter looks at us from the wall, where he hangs next to the crucifix, on which is written only one word: justice.
That’s what they said was denied to the family.
“The state officials treated me like an old gossip girl, an unsatisfied disturber of peace.
They want people to just believe everything they say and keep quiet.
But it’s not right, it’s not possible, especially when there are so many violations and shortcomings around,” she says.
Wearing a presidential tie on Saturday, President Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto will take on a difficult responsibility with her.
Over the past six years, tens of thousands of families in Mexico have been affected by violence-related crimes, and the new president has promised to make addressing the issue a priority during his presidency.
“I hope he will be exactly the same president that he was as governor,” says Olvera, a congressman from Valle de Bravo from the PRI party.
However, that is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Ness are most afraid of.
Bradley Manning has not complained of ill-treatment, the prosecution claims.
Prosecutors are trying to refute Bradley Manning’s allegations of poor detention conditions.
The hearing focused on Manning's stay in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defence demands that the case be closed on the grounds that Manning’s conditions of detention were cruel.
The U.S. military is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents.
On Friday, the prosecution tried to prove that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified material in U.S. history, did not take advantage of numerous opportunities to file a complaint of ill-treatment, which he said he had to endure while in the military.
During the cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Meade, Maryland, the military prosecutor Major Ashden Feyn stated that the records of Manning's weekly visits by the prison administration for nine months of his detention in Quantico, Virginia, were not severable.
A cross-examination of the defence's application to terminate Manning's case on the grounds that the conditions of his detention were cruel and in itself sufficient punishment was conducted the day after Manning stated that he intended to commit suicide while in detention.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 has been charged with the theft of several thousand classified documents during his service in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published on the Internet on the WikiLeaks website.
WikiLeaks did not confirm that the source of the information was Manning.
During Friday's hearing, Prosecutor Fein along with Manning reviewed the reports, which were filled out after Manning's visits by administration officials during his stay in Quantico prison, where he was under strict detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Prosecutor Fein asked about the reports on Friday, Manning admitted that he considered the prison administration’s treatment of him as “excellent” and the general conditions of detention as “very professionally organized.”
The reports in question do not contain complaints of ill-treatment, despite Manning being asked directly about the conditions of its contents, Feyn argues.
Manning replied that he had expressed verbal concern about these problems and that the administration officials who had visited him had discussed these problems with him and stated that they would deal with them but had not recorded them in writing.
“They recorded ‘no problems’ (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn’t mean I didn’t raise the issue in the conversation,” Manning says.
A military judge, Colonel Denise Linde, also asked Manning why he had not complained of ill-treatment to him in January 2011 during a commission hearing considering the suicidal intentions he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning responded that during that meeting he wanted to have the “preventing injury” regime removed and the conditions of detention relaxed.
The military leadership explained that a limited detention regime – at a level lower than the suicide-prevention surveillance regime – was introduced to protect the prisoner, as well as the safety of others.
“I wanted to let the administration know that I’m okay with them cancelling the trauma prevention regime ... so that my life level improves, from my point of view,” Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to a prison at a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that he had thoughts of suicide in Kuwait, and that one day he lost consciousness due to severe heat.
He explained that it is psychologically very difficult when you are not told how your fate is decided and what is happening in the outside world.
“My world has shrunk to the base of Camp Ariphant, to the size of my prison,” Manning said Thursday.
“I thought I was going to die in this cage.”
While in Quantico, Manning said he spent most of his time in a small cell — at least 21 hours, and often more than 23 hours a day — in complete solitude.
Manning reports that he was allowed to leave only a mattress, blanket, slippers, several items of clothing and glasses.
He says he tried to move, as sleeping or even just lying in the daytime prohibited the rules.
According to Manning, in his sleep, his eyes were constantly struck by light penetrating from outside the camera.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned in bed at night, then, according to him, he was woken and forced to turn his back.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal objection to Manning's wrongful treatment in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Livenworth, Kansas.
In addition, on Friday, the judge questioned Manning about a statement he made while testifying on Thursday that, after being forced to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico one night, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners at a morning check.
Manning said he was unable to cover himself with a blanket during the inspection.
Responding to a judge’s question on Friday, Manning said he understood from a guard’s order that he should drop a blanket that he could hide, but admitted that no one directly ordered him to drop it.
Manning said on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of his attempt to show an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning said he told the officer that he could use a rubber band of panties or panties to injure himself, but did not.
That night, according to Manning, his underwear, slippers and glasses were taken from the camera.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account what he has had to go through during his detention and will significantly reduce his sentence if Manning is found guilty by a military court that is due to begin hearing his case early next year.
The defense said it plans to offer Manning to plead guilty to less serious crimes and challenge other charges as excessive.
The reopening of the hearings is scheduled for this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to insist that the conditions of detention have been justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was detained at Quantico in accordance with rules governing the detention of those arrested under the most stringent regime.
The charges against Manning include complicity with the enemy, illegal facilitation of the publication of data on the Internet, the transfer of information relating to national defense, and the theft of state property or documents.
If convicted under all paragraphs of the indictment, he could face life imprisonment.
My crisis of national self-determination is the story of an American of Mexican origin.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico due to the lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who left because they remind the people of the country of difficult times.
Ruben Navarrette believes that Mexicans of American origin are torn between two cultures.
During a recent trip to Mexico City, I passed through the arrivals corridor, approached the border control zone and froze on the spot.
The signs indicated two lines: one for Mexicanos (Mexicans), the second for Extranjeros (foreigners).
I stood in front of them for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in Central California, and I've been called a Mexican all my life.
It’s just a conventional name, like how my friends in Boston call themselves Irish, and friends in New York consider themselves Italian.
Later, I stopped at the complex design of “American of Mexican origin”.
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather’s homeland, there was no need for conditional names or complex constructions.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask questions or answer them.
But my vocabulary is poorer than the speakers of the language, and I can’t get rid of the American accent.
That's why I got my U.S. passport and turned in for Extranjeros.
I recalled this story a few days ago when newly elected Mexican President Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto visited the White House and met with President Obama.
On the agenda were the usual issues for the meetings of the presidents of these countries: immigration, drugs and trade.
President Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto willingly spoke about the rise of the Mexican economy, thanks to which Mexicans will now, with the same success, be able to stay in Mexico, instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to conclude a partnership agreement with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc like the European Union.
In addition, President Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no specific proposals were made.
For Mexico, relations with the United States are a difficult and time-honored issue.
Most Americans never thought about the fact that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and, under the tutelage of rifles, forced its leaders to abandon half of their territory.
But Mexicans think for centuries, not minutes, and see reminders of those events in everything.
Therefore, it is only necessary for any U.S. statesman to moan at least a word of criticism towards Mexico, in the press and among the elites of Mexican society immediately distributed complaints that Americans are encroaching on the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the descendants of Montezuma are filled with belligerence.
At the same time, Mexico’s relationship with more than 35 million Americans of Mexican origin living in the United States is the most complex.
Want to talk about insults?
They're enough.
In Mexico there are winners and losers, people who find opportunities in this country for themselves, and those for whom there are no such opportunities.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio, so many people of Mexican descent have only one reason: at some point in their family history, someone – a father or grandfather – had no opportunity to realize himself in Mexico and was forced to go north.
Most often, they were Mexicans of a certain type - sluggish, poorly educated, from poor peasant families.
We are their descendants, and we remember that.
In Mexico, they see it differently.
Today, our life is the embodiment of the American dream, we studied in good schools and got a good job, but we do not forget that even this dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confused and unclear, but we know which country to consider as our own.
United States of America.
Besides, we know that the majority of the Mexican elite and the ruling class do not like us.
We answer them the same.
They see us as a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us as second-class people, as non-real Mexicans.
We do not speak Spanish well enough, and our ties with Mexico are not strong enough.
Our very existence for them is explained by failures.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they would not have left.
We would not be behind a silk curtain now, finding a rich life in the United States, but losing spiritual ties.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and legally moved to the United States as a child, and this reminds me that there are certain frictions between real Mexicans and Americans of Mexican origin - Mexicans understand their national identity more clearly, and Americans of Mexican origin it.
She is a U.S. citizen and believes she belongs to both countries.
At the same time, many of my fellow Americans of Mexican descent do not feel belonging to any of them.
We listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
When you get the best of both worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
We are Americans in Mexico.
In the United States, we are called Mexicans.
Now, as I found out during my trip, as if our relations were not already sufficiently complicated, some Mexican leaders and representatives of the intelligentsia want to restore relations with the diaspora.
They want Americans of Mexican descent to work as ambassadors to Mexico and represent their interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends about what a beautiful country it is and how great it is to visit, and we could convince political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah, of course.
Nothing's gonna work out.
Too many insults in the past.
And given the gap between the rich and the poor, the rampant corruption and drug trafficking, many of us do not consider this country so beautiful.
I'm sorry, but deal with it yourself, amigos.
And that's fair.
If some Mexicans still can’t forgive the United States for what they did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they’ll have to accept the fact that some Mexican Americans are still offended by how their relatives have been treated in Mexico recently.
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
Maybe we have more in common than I thought.
The Old Battles in the New Middle East
A cease-fire agreement between Israel and the Hamas group could become a fragile foundation for a future world.
Is a long-term peace between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East possible?
Another round of bloodshed leads to the conclusion that such hopes are in vain.
The usual, meaningless disputes about who started it first sound; many buildings are turned into ruins; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, have been killed, and six Israelis have been killed; for the first time during the conflict, rockets fired from the territory of the Gaza Strip have fallen in the vicinity of the capital.
However, despite the fact that the Israelis and Palestinians have hopelessly entwined in their age-old conflict, changes have come to the Middle East.
This can be treated in different ways, but the events of the “Arab Spring” have surrounded many established realities in a storm of rebellion, and Palestinians and Israelis have failed to stay away from the vortex that shook the region.
Perhaps, as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons to hope for a way out of this deadly stalemate.
War Without Winners
At first glance, the situation does not give cause for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, which was signed on November 21, will be implemented, the clashes this week have only strengthened the positions of the security forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Islamist Hamas movement, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, say they have forced Israel to back down despite the losses they have suffered.
Despite the fact that some leaders of the group have been destroyed, and 1.7 million residents are blocked in one of the most densely populated and troubled corners of our planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is growing in popularity on the West Bank of the Jordan River, another Palestinian territory currently controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well conclude that time is working for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new influential and rich friends.
A resurgent regional leader, Turkey, which was once Israel’s closest ally among Muslim countries, has come out in support of Hamas; her example was followed by Qatar, one of the Gulf’s richest and most dynamically developing states.
Hamas supporters are calling for the creation of an Islamist crescent moon around Israel, from Lebanon in the north, ruled by a paramilitary Hezbollah group, to Syria, where increasingly pro-Islamist rebels are about to overthrow Bashar al-Assad’s power, and then to the kingdom of Yor.
The most significant change in the balance of power in the region occurred on the southern borders of Israel, in the most populous and important Arab country, in Egypt, where under President Mohamed Morsi the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood movement was strengthened.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator who paid little attention to supporting Hamas.
The Muslim Brotherhood, on the other hand, is an organization much like Hamas, and its leaders are more prone to populism.
In future diplomatic situations, Hamas may become a significant player, whose voice will not be silenced even by Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the “hard” line in Israel will come to the opposite conclusion.
In the military sense, Hamas was defeated.
Israel’s Iron Dome anti-missile system justified the cost of its creation and successfully destroyed many of the launched Hamas missiles.
The citizens of Israel can sleep peacefully for at least some time.
As for diplomacy, the United States remained true to its unwavering position; many European countries also blamed Hamas for the start of the last round of violence.
Another important factor is the economic prosperity of Israel, especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, who largely ignored the peace process.
Despite the fact that since 2004, about 30 Israelis have been killed by rockets fired from the Gaza Strip, Israel has not managed to minimize the problem of terrorists-killers, in part due to the wall that enters the West Bank of the Jordan River - a significant part of the state is not recognized.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party - in preparation for the elections scheduled for January 22nd - has been united with even more aggressive conservatives led by Avigdor Lieberman, is very convenient.
What is the point of worshipping the Palestinians and giving them their own state?
If they are given all the power in the West Bank, will they not start launching rockets at Israel from there, as their fellow citizens in the Gaza Strip do?
It is better to keep them behind the wall and hard suppress any attempts to raise their heads.
Supporters of the “hard” line may win; however, their calculations may be refuted in the Arab Spring.
While Islamists, who come to power in Egypt and other countries, do not have the warmest feelings for Israel, their priority will be domestic problems.
Israel’s defense budget is larger than all of its Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with a regional superpower is unlikely to help Arab governments strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of President Morsi, who worked with Barack Obama to end the fire, is a good sign and could mark the beginning of change.
Israel, no less, must take into account the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic change unfolds in Arab countries, the deprivation of Palestinian self-determination is a slow-moving bomb that will sooner or later explode in Israeli-occupied territories, like a bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression already undermines the foundations of democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic aspect – the growth of the Arab population – only exacerbates these problems.
The bloody operations that are carried out every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement have to be paid for by the growing discontent of the international community.
Both sides need an external impulse.
The only solution that remains to be called upon tirelessly by sane representatives from both sides, as well as much of the rest of the world and our newspaper, is the formation of two states and the surrender of territories by Israel in exchange for security.
There remains hope, not too impressive in the short term, that the ceasefire will allow other countries to influence the sides of the conflict more effectively.
Egypt, which has long decided to cut off arms supplies to the Gaza Strip, as well as Turkey and Qatar, has a more favourable position than ever before in order to persuade Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish state adopted since 1967, taking into account the exchange of territories and the sharing of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile the Hamas and Fatah movements.
This would do more to create a Palestinian state than an upcoming UN vote that could result in recognition of Palestine’s virtual statehood.
President Obama must also play his part in putting Israel at the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never presented his own plan for a peaceful settlement.
Upon his return to the White House, he continues to show reluctance to join in on the issue.
This is a disastrously short-sighted position.
The United States is vitally interested in stability in the Middle East.
This is possible only in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
In Australia, the Uniform Packaging for Cigarettes Act has come into force.
Warnings about the harm of smoking and images of diseased parts of the body are contrasted on gloomy green boxes, the same for all brands of cigarettes.
The first in the world practice Australian law on the same type of packaging of cigarettes and tobacco products came into force, replacing the logos and color design of different brands with the same box of gloomy-olive color with terrible pictures of the diseased parts of the body and images of children whose smoking is healthy.
In addition to the different pictures and inscriptions warning about the harm of smoking, the only difference between the packs, introduced mandatory from this Saturday - the names of the stamps, which are printed in the same small font.
These are the most severe conditions in the world for packaging tobacco products.
The federal government of Australia says that the goal of this measure is to keep young people from smoking, depriving them of this harmful habit of fashion status.
This decision was based on the results of studies that showed that people who did not start smoking before the age of 26 years, in 99 cases out of 100 never become smokers.
“Obviously, even at a very young age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey through packaging,” Health Minister Tanya Plibersek said, citing research showing that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated with the idea of a princess.
Australia is one of the countries with the lowest share of smokers in the world, so these changes will not have a significant impact on the profits of transnational corporations, but other countries are already considering such measures.
Representatives of the tobacco industry strongly opposed the adoption of this law.
Tobacco companies claim that this will only increase the share of the black market in which cheap and affordable cigarettes will be sold.
“This law will lead to serious consequences other than those conceived by its initiators,” said Scott McIntyre, a spokesman for British American Tobacco in Australia.
Manufacturers of counterfeit goods from China and Indonesia will supply much more of such goods for sale on the streets of Australia.
For some, on the contrary, the new laws contribute to the growth of business.
Sandra Ha of the small family company Zico Import Pty Ltd claims that the demand for cigars and silicone cases that hide unpleasant pictures on the packaging has grown rapidly (virtually from scratch) since two months ago such companies as British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan sued.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold about six thousand products to wholesalers and is expecting a new batch.
This is a good business for us.
A potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures is, according to experts, the popularity of social networks among precisely the part of the population to which these measures are directed.
After Australia passed a series of laws that made cigarette advertising illegal and supported sports events, as well as prohibiting sellers from displaying cigarettes in a prominent place, tobacco advertising moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned local companies and websites from placing ads on the network, but it cannot restrict foreign sites from doing so.
“If you’re trading tobacco products and you only have this small loophole left, the idea of promoting your product online will seem extremely tempting to you,” said Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes an increase in reviews of brands written by allegedly ordinary users on social networks such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
The question arises - is it really a matter of the hands of a private citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he did not regret the effort and time and made a video, or is it behind the advertising company?
The Australian branch of British American Tobacco says the industry is now more concerned with adapting to the new rules than with advertising.
Representatives of the tobacco industry have even taken measures such as sponsoring Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: these states make claims within the framework of the World Trade Organization, claiming that trade has been subjected to unfair restrictions, despite the fact that the trade relations of all these countries with Australia are not perfect.
The WTO decision is expected by mid-2013.
According to Tani Plibersek, the government discussed with other countries the possibility of adopting similar packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada was the first to introduce mandatory placement of smoking-preventing photos.
This rule is now adopted in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
The possibility of tightening laws is being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia are demonstratively not following the innovations.
These pictures don't bother me.
I'm just not paying attention.
“You just grab a cigarette and hide the packet in your pocket,” explains Victor El Heig, who buys cigarettes with a photograph of the mouth tumor on the packet.
To be honest, the only thing that can make me quit is my little daughter.
James Yu, head of the King of the Pack tobacco store in central Sydney, says that the same packaging has complicated the task of placing goods on shelves
“I used to have an hour to unload the new party, and now four hours,” he complains.
"The government had to take and completely ban cigarettes, we would then say: what to do, okay, it's over, we close the store," he says, taking his hands up.
Getting bored in the world of electronic networks and constant connections is not so bad.
On this Thanksgiving, I suddenly had to spend five hours at the airport, because our plane had mechanical problems and was replaced by another plane, which we were waiting for.
So I had plenty of time to think about the nature of boredom.
I'm not gonna cheat on you.
A half-day at the airport waiting for a flight is really boring, and neither books, magazines, iPhones, nor even duty-free shops will help much here.
However, recently, more and more scientists and specialists on child development are speaking in favor of boredom.
They say that in certain situations for us and for our children to miss is not so bad.
This forces the brain to be distracted by interesting related topics, which may contribute to creativity.
And since in the modern world we are all constantly in front of some screen, the advantages of boredom pass us by.
Maybe we need to get bored?
Oh, yeah.
And at the same time, no.
We'll get back to that.
In the past, I, like many, believed that boredom was an invention of relatively recent times, when people had more free time.
This is not so, says Peter Tui, professor of Greek and Roman history at the Canadian University of Calgary, author of the book “The Fascinating History of Boredness” (Boredom: A Lively History, Yale University Press, 2011).
“In fact, boredom can boast of a very ancient history,” he says.
On the walls of Pompeii are found Latin inscriptions about boredom, dating back to the first century.
The question remains as to how we understand boredom.
The problem is, says John D. Eastwood, an adjunct professor at York University in Ontario, Canada, that the understanding and vision of boredom has often changed.
After studying the research materials on this topic and asking a target group of 100 people a question, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the following definition: boredom is when people “want to, but cannot, engage in, what would bring them satisfaction.”
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a bored person doesn’t do something they would like to do.
I don’t want to do anything with apathy.
The main thing in the experienced boredom, he says, is “a disturbance of attention and the associated deterioration of mood and the feeling that time is slowly stretching.”
According to the description, boredom can seem very similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood argues that despite the possible link between these conditions, bored people see the causes of problems in the world around them and circumstances, and people experiencing depression see problems in themselves.
Sometimes we think we’re bored when it’s really hard for us to focus on something.
In his study, Unoccupied Mind: Determining Boring in Attention, published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues refer to a previously conducted experiment in which participants listened to a recording of a voice reading the journal.
Some participants also heard loud sounds not related to the TV program included in the neighboring room, others heard the same sounds at low volume, so that they could hardly be disassembled, and the third group listened only to the recording of the voice without a foreign soundtrack.
Those participants who heard the low-volume TV noted that they were bored, more often than others – they found it difficult to concentrate, but they didn’t know the reasons for this and attributed it to boredom.
When we try to focus on a difficult or exciting task, interrupting attention can cause boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, an associate professor of neurology at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when we do something uninteresting, such as looking at the flow of products on the conveyor in search of marriage, distracting music can help avoid boredom.
It’s believed that when people start rocking on a chair or drawing caracules on a sheet of paper, they do it out of boredom, but now we know that actually such actions just help not to relax physically.
“The study found that children who are not banned from rowing and spinning learn better and remember more information than children who are required to sit quietly,” says Professor Fenske.
At some point, we all experience boredom: when the flight is delayed (as in my case), listening to a monotonous speech, watching an uninteresting movie.
However, different people have different degrees of boredom.
In the 1980s, to measure such individual features, the researchers developed a special “tenderness to boredom” scale.
Questions and assertions are used to determine the score on such a scale, such as "A lot of what I have to do is monotonous and monotonous" or "I'm too interested in too much, so there's not enough time for anything."
With the help of such questionnaires, the researchers determined that boys miss girls more often, - says Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, - especially in the presence of a variety of external stimuli.
However, in general, teenagers often miss.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of personal and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he used a pager to reach nearly 400 teenagers and their parents 7-8 times a day.
It got the following results: 32% of teens said they were bored at school and while doing homework, and 23% said they were bored outside of school.
Only 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson notes that he has no data on what such data on boredom would be like now, 21 years later.
However, he knows that “adolescents have a high tendency to be bored,” mainly because children and teenagers are not allowed to fully decide what to do.
Let’s go back to my original question: is boredom helpful?
Sometimes not, because in extreme manifestations, it can, as studies show, push people to absurd and dangerous physical actions, risky gambling, or abuse of certain substances in attempts to get rid of boredom.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have thought about the connection between boredom and creativity, says Professor Vodanovich, who has devoted more than two decades to studying this problem.
“That’s how our brain tells us that we should do something else; that’s boring,” says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
However, this same brain does not always know what to do best.
If you’re bored and you channel that energy into playing guitar or cooking experiences, you’ll do better.
However, if you start watching TV, you will only get better for a while, and soon it will pass.
Therefore, if your child misses and you give him an iPad, he will stop missing, but he will not learn to fight boredom on his own or in any other way manage his time and employment,” says Professor Fenske.
“And such self-regulation skills are used in a wide variety of situations,” he says.
Your child not only learns to do something on their own, he also learns self-control in general.
I don't think boredom should be celebrated in any way.
However, to consider it a bad thing is also not worth it.
Rather, you should learn to feel comfortable even outside of a continuous stream of action and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees with that.
“We see this so that we need to experience boredom more often, while boredom is an extremely unpleasant, irresistible desire to do something meaningful,” he says.
In fact, people tend to somehow disconnect from constant worries and just relax.
“In today’s world, we are used to the constant overstimulation of the senses,” he says, “and when silence comes, we get lost and don’t know what to do.”
It is not yet clear how the new law on the legalization of marijuana will be applied in the state of Colorado.
Anthony Orosko, a nineteen-year-old soccer player and public college student in southeastern Colorado, is accused of committing a criminal offense that will soon be completely legal across the state: storing a small portion of marijuana and the pipe in which he was smoking it.
Mr. Orosco said that one day in September he and his friends were in Lamar and were driving in a prairie car near the Kansas border when they were stopped by police.
After a police officer found marijuana in his car, Mr. Orosco was sent to court for drug possession and possession of a drug-use device — minor offenses, each of which is subject to a $100 fine — and the court date was set.
“We are treated like criminals,” Mr. Orosco says.
But is he a criminal?
As a result of the uncertainty that persists just weeks after Colorado voted to legalize the use of marijuana in small amounts for entertainment, the resolution of hundreds of small court cases depends not so much on the law as on the venue.
Accusations of petty marijuana-related offenses are already being dropped in hundreds of cases here and in Washington State, which has taken a similar measure.
Police stations have already stopped charging people aged 21 and over for storing small doses, which will be considered legal as soon as the law comes into force in a couple of weeks.
However, in more conservative Colorado counties, prosecutors have decided to review existing marijuana-related cases and continue to hold the drug liable.
At the same time, in some cities from the suburbs of Denver to the mountainous areas of the West, voters are voting to prevent the emergence of new, state-licensed marijuana stores in their places.
“It’s all moving so fast that I don’t even know what to expect next,” says Daniel J. Outs, a police chief in the town of Aurora, east of Denver.
Representatives of the controlling bodies in Washington state also puzzled to scratch their heads.
They will have to form rules to determine the procedure for licensing the cultivation, processing, distribution and sale of marijuana, and all this must be done by December 1, 2013.
They say that Colorado, good or bad, is ahead of most other states in resolving marijuana use issues, first for medical purposes, and now for entertainment.
“There’s a more orderly market in Colorado, so they’ll serve as a good example,” explains Brian I. Smith, a representative of the Council on the Regulation of Alcohol Production and Sales in Washington State.
But now no one can do more, Mr. Smith admits, than put forward some proposals and hope that it will work.
“We don’t have a real precedent that we could focus on,” he says.
The Washington State bill, called I-502, will go into effect on Dec. 6 and throw the state into a state of uncertainty for a whole year when there is no state licensing system yet, and the right to own marijuana is already legal.
And there are still difficult technical aspects to solve in this period, for example, how to find a balance between the state's order on "adequate access" to licensed marijuana with a ban on its trade at a distance of 1000 feet from schools, parks, playgrounds and kindergartens.
“It will be particularly difficult to place licensed marijuana businesses within the city limits, particularly in Seattle and its suburbs,” said Ben Livingston, a representative of the newly established research group, the Center for Marijuana Legalization.
On November 21, police chief Oates of Aurora sent an e-mail to his subordinates saying that the city's prosecutor's office would no longer hold people under the age of 21 responsible for possession of a small amount of marijuana, and that the police would stop charging people with these violations.
Police chief Oates said police would monitor compliance in the city with rules governing the activities of marijuana growers for medical purposes and would prosecute illegal drug traffickers and drug dealers.
The Weld County Attorney in North Colorado, Ken Buck, presents a more rigorous approach to the issue.
Following the vote on the bill, he stated that the prosecution would continue to hold marijuana to account, primarily in order to encourage its users to undergo treatment.
At present, 119 individuals have been charged with possession of two or less ounces of marijuana, although many of them are also charged with other offences.
“It is the duty of our institution to prosecute acts that are considered criminal at the time of their commission,” Mr. Buck said in a statement.
The reaction was mixed even in places such as the rural district of Mesa, where voters rejected a proposal to legalize marijuana.
Police in Grand Junction, the largest city in the county, no longer hold adults responsible for possession of a small amount of the drug.
District Attorney Pete Hutzinger supported the decision, but also decided not to drop the charges in open cases related to marijuana storage.
“I believe that it is our direct duty to ensure compliance with the law until it is changed,” he says.
Despite the fact that 55% of Colorado residents who took part in the vote supported this decision, including marijuana use issues for entertainment in the state and legal system will not be easy.
And the contradictory reaction of residents in different places of the state revealed the ambiguity of the attitude of the local authorities to the experiment of the state with marijuana.
“There is a cultural barrier for district prosecutors on this issue,” said Sean McAllister, a Denver lawyer representing the interests of those convicted of marijuana possession, and a local representative of the National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws.
“They’ve been persecuting people for so long that they can’t really put up with the fact that it’s no longer a crime,” he says.
Colorado and Washington — the first states to have a small amount of marijuana in the same way as alcohol — are destined to become an experimental field on a country-wide scale to test the very idea of legalizing drugs.
Supporters of legalization and state officials plan to expand the territory of legalized trade, but at the same time, they are anxiously awaiting instructions from the federal authorities, who still plan to view the sale and cultivation of marijuana as federal crimes.
Supporters of the legalization of marijuana hope that the Office of Justice will concede on this issue.
Despite several widespread arrests of marijuana traffickers and patients on medical records, the federal government has in most cases done well to trade marijuana for medical purposes in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states.
Agents of the Bureau of Narcotics Control are unlikely to break into homes to confiscate a small bag of marijuana, but they are unlikely to turn a blind eye to state-regulated recreational marijuana stores that are allowed under the new law, Kevin A. Sabet says, advising against the issue.
Some cities in Colorado did not wait for the actions of the federal authorities.
Even before the presidential election, some local administrations approved a moratorium on the opening of new shops for the sale of marijuana, which would not have been able to open sooner than a year.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the western part of the state, proposed a six-month ban on marijuana trade, which is likely to be approved next week.
“We don’t want to be in a position where we’re going to give someone a license and then it’s going to cause serious problems at the federal level,” said Bob Nicholson, a city council member.
Our city voted against this amendment.
And now we have a contradiction between the results of the local vote and what the state voted for.
There are still a lot of unresolved issues.
Petronella Wyatt: I survived Oxford for being a Conservative.
The persecution of university students for their views did not begin today.
For as long as I can remember, I've always dreamed of going to Oxford University.
My father and older brother studied at Oxford and described it as the world’s best educational institution, a modern analogue of an ancient symposium that laid the two foundations of civilization – freethinking and tolerance.
And yet, after two weeks of studying at the historic faculty of Worcester College at Oxford University in the late 1980s, I picked up my suitcases and left, which turned out to be the first real scandal in my life.
My father couldn't stand it and cried.
My friends were upset with me.
The Evening Standard claimed that I dropped out of college because I didn’t like my classmates having sex in the next room.
The writer E. Normann Wilson joked that I had to leave because I had to drink from the cracked cups.
Actually, it wasn't all that much fun.
I ran away.
Yes, I escaped because I was systematically harassed and intimidated.
Not at all because of my rather unusual name or the fact that I was studying in a private school.
I was harassed for only one reason, and in this glorified cradle of enlightenment it seemed like a real barbarism and blind fanaticism: my father, now deceased Woodrow Wyatt, was a well-known adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I myself was a supporter of the Conservatives.
You may ask, why do you think about it now?
According to the latest data, a new generation of students who adhere to right-center views is subjected to the same harassment.
This institutionalized and ever-growing hatred for conservative students in Oxford is so strong that last week a group of such students demanded the same protection of their rights as that afforded to disabled people, sexual and ethnic minorities.
Conservatives at Corpus Christi College’s student club in Cambridge state that they are “often actively isolated, subjected to personal attacks and made to feel unwanted guests” because of their political views.
They want to introduce an additional representative to the college's Equal Rights Committee to ensure freedom of expression.
Their situation was only aggravated by the recent BBC 2 documentary about politics in the student environment “The Wonderland: Young, Smart and Right”, in which conservatives were presented by eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
The film featured Joe Cook, a former president of the Oxford University Conservatives Association who rides in a roller-coaster, wears a silver suit and a cane with a silver saddlebag.
At other universities, conservative students complain that they are making “dismissal goats” because of higher tuition fees.
Luke Black, 20, the vice president of the University of Nottingham’s Conservatives Association, said in an interview with one of Sunday’s newspapers that “the university environment is increasing the bias toward left-wing views.
People who don’t even know us consider us in advance to be the brazen and unpunished children of rich parents.”
Samuel Roberts, 21, a student at the historic faculty of Corpus Christi College who was asked to step up his defense, calls the atmosphere "inconvenient," and Stephanie Cherill, 19, the new president of the Oxford University Conservatives Association, says that the attitude of members of the student's club is "inconvenient."
“This poses a threat to both the atmosphere of intellectual discussion and the normal life of the club members,” she says.
The first few weeks at Oxford I was not just in the minority, I was alone.
I arrived there in September 1986, a shy and shy eighteen-year-old girl.
Oxford was feverish in its hatred of the Conservative Party.
A year earlier, the university had voted to deprive former student Margaret Thatcher of her honorary degree due to a reduction in budget allocations for higher education.
Even the Stalinists would be uncomfortable in such an atmosphere.
In the first days of the first week of the first year, when the students met each other and the teachers, I felt for the first time what was waiting for me ahead.
I did not yet know that the teachers not only looked through their fingers at the enthusiasm of conservative students, but also gladly took part in it.
Political issues – the miners’ strike, privatization, and the government’s refusal to apply sanctions against the apartheid government in South Africa – penetrated through the wooden-paneled walls of the auditoriums.
At my first seminar I had to translate the French text of the eighteenth century into English, and I was not prepared for what followed.
"Miss Wyatt," said the teacher, now deceased Harry Pitt, "please translate the first paragraph."
The text was difficult for me, I was stuck.
Harry Pitt was a very bile person with a cake-like face.
"Thatcherists don't learn French in principle or they just lack brains?" he asked.
The other students nodded.
I had tears in my eyes.
“I advise you to take a few initial lessons of French in your spare time, if you’re certainly not very busy circling around in society,” he said.
I returned to my room completely unlucky.
That night in college, I was sitting at lunch alone; then someone patted me on the shoulder.
It was James, a second-year student from the Faculty of English who introduced himself as a member of the University's Conservatives Association.
“I know who you are,” he said friendlyly.
- Unfortunately, the case is as follows:
Everyone who is suspected of being sympathetic to the Conservatives will be mocked.
It's not easy for me, and in your case, they know that your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it'll be harder for you.
Most of the first-year conservatives pretend to be Labour.”
Later, at a local pub, I tried to be cowardly.
I insisted that I didn't agree with everything Margaret Thatcher said.
The trick didn't work.
A first-year student at the Faculty of Philosophy, Politics and Economics, who himself studied at Eton, said: “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You're contagious."
Other students took up his words.
I was spoiled, dirty.
“How do conservatives have sex?” one of them asked.
"They're hitting each other, aren't they?"
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt until the abolition of criminal prosecution in the sixties.
Will I ever be able to live a normal life in Oxford?
Or will I have to meet with like-minded people only under the cover of the night?
Will I be forced to become a Labour and hide my true beliefs?
The next three years seemed like hell, full of persecution and loneliness.
The only teacher in my college who didn’t hide his conservative views was Norman Stone, a professor of modern history.
He was hated not only for belonging to the Conservatives, but also for being Thatcher’s foreign policy adviser and one of its spokesmen.
He barely showed up at college.
He despised it for its provinciality, finesse and commitment to the Marxist-Determinist view of history.
In 1997 he took a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here," he told me.
I started to travel to Oxford from my parents’ house in London, trying to find refuge among relatives and unbiased friends of the capital.
I told my father I hated Oxford and explained the reason.
He didn't believe me.
During his studies in the forties, any political views were accepted there.
“But it’s the best university in the world,” he said lamentably.
- They can't do that there, except in the city of sleeping spires...
Even my communist friends have always behaved flawlessly.”
His wet eyes were blurry.
“Don’t make hasty decisions.
I'm sure it's just a joke.
You'll break my heart if you drop out of college."
I was tired of constant trips to London and my emotional defenses were weak.
My friend, also a conservative, could not stand the pressure and gave up his beliefs.
The next week during the seminar, when the next history teacher took me very seriously as the “enemy of the people,” I decided to do the same.
In my heart of shame, I admitted that "I was brainwashed by my parents" and called them "old fools."
The breath was short.
The last nail in the coffin of my career at Oxford was destined to kill my father.
At the time, he wrote two columns each week for publications owned by Rupert Murdoch.
My door was locked.
I didn't go out, and five minutes later, my pursuers surrendered.
When they left, I picked up my suitcase and boarded the first train to London.
I never came back.
You can call me a squid and a squid.
But at the age of eighteen, no one should become the object of such anger and intimidation in a school.
The saddest thing is that it was Oxford, which not only released fourteen Tory prime ministers, but to this day hides behind the undeserved reputation of a university in which equality and freedom are valued.
"Valentino prefers elegance to fame"
About the exhibition "Valentino: Master of Sewing", which opened this week in London, ABC talks with Nati Abascal, Fiona Tissen-Bornemica and other famous clients of the Italian designer
Somerset House, the former residence of Queen Elizabeth I of England, is the only place in the British capital to host an exhibition about Valentino Garavani.
The designer acknowledged this during the opening of Valentino: Master of Sewing, a triumphant retrospective exhibition that brings together more than 130 high fashion dresses created by his “home” over the past 50 years.
“I love this palace,” he says with his unique Italian accent.
This exhibition is the final part of the story, the only character of which is "El Signore" Garavani, but it could not have been written without his famous clients.
Valentino has always felt charmed by the rare and distant world to know.
In the first hall of this exhibition, open until March 3, will abound with personal letters and photographs signed by the most noble aristocrats, from Princess Salima Aga Khan to Lord Snowden, including Marie Chantal, Princess of Greece, and Margaret, Princess of Great Britain.
Valentino shows these personal memories as trophies of his social rise: from the modest porter from the city of Voghera in northern Italy to the idol of the international “elite”.
Being in love with the royal court is not a bad thing.
“They don’t even put out their cigarette butts on your gorgeous carpet like some of the great pop stars do,” says Baroness Fiona Tissen-Bornemitz.
In the 60s and 70s we both lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is an incomparable host and welcomes guests with generosity and elegance.
“We all loved coming to his chalet in the Gstaad,” explains ex-wife Heini Tissen, a close friend of forgotten beauties such as Marella Agnelli or Evgenia Niarchos.
Valentino has always preferred elegance to fame.
Despite this, he is a star.
Valeria Macza, representing Valentino
The Argentinian model Valeria Mazza recalls a charismatic modeler.
One day we went to dinner at his house, it was after the fashion show in the square of Spain in Rome, many years ago.
Among the twenty guests were Sharon Stone and John Kennedy, Jr.
Valentino's style was manifested in everything - in every detail of his apartment, in her outfit, in food, in music.
“Valentino made each of the guests feel important and loved,” recalls the “top model”, whose work with the model began in 1995 during the Haute Couture Week in Paris.
“He never goes out of fashion because his sketches are real works of art,” she concludes.
The Parade of Genealogy
