The hardest profession in the world: miners from Kawah-Ijen
For four euros, Indonesian miners risk their lives and health by hauling 70 kilograms of sulfur to the top of the volcano on steep rocky paths
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
Among them is Anto Vijaya, one of the 400 miners who make a living by mining sulfur in Kawah-Ijen volcano, located in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day, Anto descends to the very bottom of the crater, where the sulphurous gas rising from the depths of the Earth freezes when in contact with the air.
He cuts off huge pieces of sulfur, the total weight of which can reach 70 kg, he puts them in two bamboo baskets, folds the baskets on his shoulders and carries them upstairs along a rugged stone road.
To the top of the volcano, whose height is 2,386 meters, is only 250 meters, however, it takes more than 40 minutes for the exhausted trucks to climb the tortoise step, with difficulty maintaining balance and carefully sensing the road, so as not to stumble and fall off the cliff.
They know that one wrong step can cost them their lives, as happened to one tourist from France who broke away from the Kawah-Ijen rocks a few years ago.
Kawah-Ijen miners earn 5 Eurocents for every kilogram of sulfur they extract
Being at the top, they make their way between the tourists who photograph them, as if they were circus monkeys and, tired of carrying heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the weights that the mining company has placed a little higher, at an altitude of 1,850 meters.
We are talking about PT Kandy Ngrimbi, an enterprise that has been operating this volcano since 1960 and, better yet, its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euros cents) for every kilogram of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to petrochemical production, because this mineral is common in everyday life and is used for making matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for bleaching sugar.
“Since the norm is to carry 70 kilograms, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each walk,” explains Anto, who usually performs three daily transfers.
He spends three hours on each of them and at the end feels broken, but they allow him to accumulate 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) by the end of the day.
Although it seems a squalor for such an inhumane effort, it is three times more than he would earn in the field.
“The daily wage for miners is very high according to local standards, where the collection of coffee is paid 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) per day and the average monthly earnings is two million rupees (167 euros),” explains the trucker, who previously worked as a stonemason on the tourist island of Bali.
There his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the plot was not so heavy, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a good reason, which in Indonesia is as crushing as sulfur: "I married a girl from Bali, and I took her to another place."
Anto has asthma, he breathes hard, constantly coughs, and his eyes tear because of toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto spent three years risking himself in Kawah-Ijen, whose sulfur had already begun to affect him despite the presence of masks and special glasses.
He has asthma, he breathes hard, constantly coughs, and his eyes tear because of the toxic gases that the volcano emits.
This is the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
“I’m going to work for another two years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French,” he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished by life, this pleasant and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or porter in a hotel, but instead he does the work of a mules.
It shares a dirty wooden hut with other carriers, it gets up every day at two o’clock in the night, because the sulfur does not stop flowing at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the dark.
Challenging the shadows, Anto descends into the crater, illuminating himself with a small lantern attached to his helmet, which he bought for his own money.
About 400 carriers are dragging baskets with gray on their shoulders from the bottom of the volcano
Despite the high profits, the mining company has not mechanized the production of sulfur to save costs and does not provide any equipment to the carriers that work on their own account and with such deprivations.
In fact, they don’t even get a portion of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) photo shoot fee, which, along with an entrance ticket for 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), guards of this reserve charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its mules.
“This is a job for cattle, not people,” says Badrusin, a 42-year-old root-carrier who has spent three decades at Kawah-Ijen since leaving college.
Able to lift up to 110 kilograms, he says he will tolerate working “as much as he can” because he needs money to educate his three children aged 18 to 10.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although the sulfur burns the throat and burns the eyes, when the wind suddenly changes and catches the miners in the dense pillars of smoke coming out of the volcano, they are so hardy that no one complains of their severe diseases... more serious, obviously, than their usual problems with the elbows and thighs.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unainik can now only lift 50 kilograms in his 53 years.
Every day he and his comrades carry 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to the warehouse in Tamansari, overcoming a distance of 18 kilometers along a narrow path among the thickets.
“I’m not going to retire, I’m going to die here because the volcano is my whole life,” Unainik says, opening his mouth wide, which lacks several teeth.
Of his five children, the oldest, 30, also works as a sulfur transporter.
Time passes, but poverty perpetuates from generation to generation one of the most difficult occupations in the world: what human mules do with Kawah-Ijen.
Singapore Seeks Children to Save the Economy
Singaporeans blame career, stress, and housing and education prices for the lack of children.
“The population of Singapore needs to grow.”
I'm a patriot's husband, you're my patriot's wife, let's do our civic duty and make a living!
It may seem incredible that these lines are part of a mint note ad, but despite this – or perhaps because of this – this video became a YouTube hit in Singapore earlier this year.
These phrases are part of a rap that uses local sayings like “Let’s put the bao (bulk) in the oven” to laugh at the birth rate in Singapore.
The advertising agency that made this video, BBH, cherishes the hope that with the help of advertising they will be able to draw attention to this problem in an entertaining way.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, says he wanted to use the power of music to make people do “his national duty.”
This thing is exclusively for the Internet, so we needed to make it fun and fun.
This is the main problem in the country.
We are the worst in the world to reproduce ourselves, so we felt that this is the topic we should touch on.
We knew that the government was trying to do a lot, for example, to launch ghosts with pheromones or organize parties of quick acquaintances (blitz-dates).
Many of these ideas may have been creative, but they didn’t necessarily work.
So we thought, why don’t we do the most creative thing we can to solve this problem, namely rap?
1.2 children
Anyone who doesn’t take it lightly is the government of Singapore.
It spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
The state package for married couples and parents provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity and maternity leave, and provides tax breaks.
But all this has low efficiency.
Singapore is a rich and high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leadership and its strict public control.
The birth rate in Singapore, according to its national population management, is currently at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was below 2 - what is known as the replacement rate - in 1976.
So why don’t Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Min, director of the National Population Administration’s Spouse and Family Policy Department, said the reason for this was “improved education” and “a wider range of career opportunities.”
“This has allowed people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, in addition to getting married and starting a family,” she explains.
These changes in social norms contribute to the increase in the number of bachelors and the postponement of marriages and childbirth, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, immigration policy, which aims to dramatically increase immigration to counter population decline, is causing outrage among the local population.
There are websites in Singapore where there is a barely concealed xenophobia against many new immigrants, especially Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and unwilling to integrate.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why Singapore’s ruling party had the worst election result since independence last year.
After the election, there was an attempt to solve the problem, using quotas and higher taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the decline in fertility has some impact on the nation’s economic growth, tax revenues, medical expenses, and immigration policy, Singapore’s example is also starting to have some unexpected consequences.
The government is making efforts not to build so much small housing.
For example, this is beginning to affect the real estate sector.
The Urban Development Manual has now passed to controlling the number of small apartments known as “shoe boxes” that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments with an area of 46 square meters are very well sold.
However, there is an opinion that they can contribute to a sloppy lifestyle and deprive the incentives of developers who want to build a large family home.
But Lim Yu Sun, CEO of home-building firm EL Developers, says their “shoe boxes” sell much faster than larger ones.
They are more popular, in the sense that such apartments are bought for a few days, even weeks, faster than larger apartments.
As a result, our income increases.
However, he acknowledges that the new rules provide clearer guidance for developers who have previously faced hurdles if they wanted to offer too many small apartments in the project.
Too much overexertion
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new rules may be a step towards increasing national fertility, after talking to Singaporeans who work in the financial district of the center, it seems they won’t have much of an effect.
“People are very stressed, housing is expensive, as is education, and because of this, many people put it off,” says the young manager.
Other people can have children.
“But it’s important for me to have my own money and time,” says another 20-year-old.
Men and women refer to their careers, stress, and housing and education prices as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So, no matter how much the government tries to encourage its citizens to have children, in terms of childbirth, the last word remains with Singaporeans.
Personal in the offline - personal in the online
Confidentiality.
According to the dictionary of the Royal Spanish Academy, it is a property of private or "the sphere of personal life, which they have the right to protect from any interference".
What is personal for a minor under the age of 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and in social networks?
Does he understand the dangers of discussing situations on the Internet that he would certainly not have shared outside the Internet?
elPeri<0xC3><0xB3>dico interviewed five boys between the ages of 10 and 15, who were frequent users of the network.
In four cases, they associated the term with “something very personal” and “password and username” when they applied it to social media.
“My biggest secrets I wouldn’t upload to a post,” says 10-year-old Jorge, as he tries to explain the importance of personal on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"It's a very secret, my mom may know them, but not the whole world," he says.
On FB I upload beautiful pictures or pictures from games.
I also have fun with my friends.
“I wouldn’t share a photo that’s not mine, or someone who’s behaving stupidly,” he says.
The boy realizes that it is bad to publish indecent photos of naked people, crimes or to write offensive or angry comments.
Jorge assures that he knows 35 friends he has on FB, and nine of his followers on Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
The mother knows she has a password to one of the accounts.
I started Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
“I don’t know if they answer me, I just download them,” he adds.
“Social media is entertainment, I can talk to distant relatives or to my friends quickly,” he says.
Without thinking, he replies that he would never accept a request from a stranger.
I wouldn't count on someone recommending him to a stranger.
The case of 14-year-old Jose is different.
This teenager has open accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, and the latter admits that he does not know 20 people added to his list of friends.
“It doesn’t scare me because we have something in common, music, for example,” he says.
According to the boy, no one trusted him and did not ask for his home address or phone number.
“If I’m being pressured or demanded, I’ll just remove them from my account,” he admits.
Jose became a follower of Ask after reading the recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is no stranger to the experience of what is now known as cybermobbing.
A friend of mine was blackmailed on social media.
He was threatened and robbed of money.
“He never knew who it was,” he said.
The victim, according to Jose, did not delete the account.
"Just turned on the privacy."
It then explains the sequence of steps to set up your account in a secure way.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or confusing situations.
Yeah, I'd do that if I didn't like the person or if I wanted to.
“Although I know it’s cybermobbing,” he confirms.
Key issues:
Marielos Porras, a teacher of English and a specialist in education and training, believes that in order to guide children and adolescents, it is necessary to understand that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
“The Internet has emerged as a means to search for information, but with the advent of these sites, the rules of the game have changed,” she notes.
Porras points out that academician Mark Prensky, a master of pedagogy at Yale University and author of Digital Aboriginals and Immigrants, invented these terms to explain the phenomenon.
Digital aborigines are those, children and young people who were born in the age of technology.
“We’re digital immigrants who have to teach them while we’re still learning,” she says.
It explains that this topic is complex, “because we ask them to have a certain criterion of what can or cannot be distributed, published or spoken, at an age when maturity is lacking for it.”
“Also make them elective, while the most important thing for them is to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences,” she adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to show what privacy is for children and adolescents is to ask questions that make them think.
“To tell them not to do it is useless,” she adds.
Then Porras lists some options: Are there things you wouldn’t tell a stranger, so why are you doing it online?
Or would you like to have a photo of you posted like the one you posted about your friend?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
When you sign photos from parties, do you ask permission from other people to mark them?
And one more thing, does everyone need to know what you're doing at every moment?
Another point is to let them know that they should behave online the same way they do offline.
The rules are the same.
“Outside the Internet, people behave with respect, responsibility and other principles, as should be in social networks,” she says.
Vigilance
Estuardo Guardia, a university lecturer, a professor of primary education and an education consultant, explains the need for heads of families to read social media policies in good faith.
Understanding each of the points, they have good grounds for talking to children about the prerequisites of opening an account online.
“For example, age and what is allowed to be distributed or published,” he says.
According to Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>, the key question is to remind children of the lesson “do not talk to strangers”.
The UNASUR summit ends without the Lima Declaration being made public
The 6th Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the announcement of the Lima Declaration, previously announced and theoretically signed by the family of mandatory participants.
The EFE has repeatedly sought access to the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of UNASUR, but sources from the Office and the Presidential Administration have indicated on the main page that it will be transmitted after the closure, but then confirmed that at some point it will be published on the Peruvian Government’s website.
On questions about the text, they pointed out that the contents were set out by the President of Peru, Olianta Umalas, during brief statements to the press.
The access of journalists to information about the Summit was always limited.
During the day, only a video of the presidential assembly without sound was broadcast, in the press room, with the message "closed meeting, sound prohibited".
Few of the information circulating among the reporters was provided by the press-secretaries of some of the UNASUR governments present at the meeting, but not the Peruvian one.
The only document circulated during the day was a list of participating presidents, which caused discontent among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Subsequently, the administration of the President of Peru sent an e-mail to the media with a “final declaration” of the summit, but it is a statement by Umalas, not an official document that ended the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the III Summit of South American and Arab Countries (ASPA), and this time, despite the insistence of the press, the so-called Lima Declaration, which was previously announced, was also not distributed.
On the official ASPA website, you can check that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities have tried to ensure that transmission systems are provided for all journalists, but to limit the receipt of information as much as possible.
The summit also concluded with a joint decision by Chile and Peru to adopt the verdict of the Hague Court, which will settle the territorial dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Olianta Umalas, and Chile, Sebasti<0xC3><0xA1>n Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era, met at a regional meeting and ratified that they would abide by the decision of the International Court of Justice, which begins on Monday in The Hague hearing statements of both sides, in the framework of the accusation that Lima has made against Santiago.
“We will abide by and enforce a decision that will clarify the differences that we are currently presenting in this international court,” Umala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile was, is, and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful settlement of disputes, pacts and international tribunals,” Piniera added, and welcomed Umalu’s handshake against the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they would submit to the International Court of Justice came immediately after Colombia objected this week to the Bogot<0xC3><0xA1> Pact, according to which it recognized compliance with the verdicts of that international court following a decision on maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered erroneous.
The summit was held in the absence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chavez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, whose membership in UNASUR has been suspended since 2011 following the impeachment of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
The incoming president, Olyanta Umalas, was responsible for opening the talks in the morning and closing the summit, just after noon Lima time.
The head of state read the final document, in which he said that 16 agreements were adopted and 31 project directions were approved among South American countries, the amount of the planned investments amounted to 17 billion dollars.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the countries of UNASUR will take “important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding the agreements on the place of residence”.
He said that actions are being taken to improve “cooperation in the fight against citizens’ insecurity and against organized transnational crime, actions to increase the availability of medicines, low-cost Internet access in all parts of South America and to take into account the risks of natural disasters in a comprehensive and effective way”.
As Europe is in crisis, “the economic unification (of Latin America) should not have a triumphant basis, but should serve to expand our production base and foresee a better future for our cities,” Umala added.
“We have decided to give the privilege to a group of 31 landmark projects that will improve the connectivity of South America’s spaces, especially in rural and border areas... uniting our countries and forming new economic schemes,” the Peruvian president said in a statement.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five relate to Peru, and are limited by the transverse axes on its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two are aimed at greater communication with Ecuador, but he did not provide more details.
The final document also touched on the political situation in Paraguay.
“We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve its re-accession to the Union of South American Nations,” from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of well-being and peace, to be united, and to have good relations among its neighbours, was another theme highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before starting to participate in the regional meeting, that he hopes to meet with his colleague from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico City to hold negotiations in a respectful manner on the maritime dispute as a result of God's faithfulness.
"After tomorrow (Saturday), I may meet with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
